President Obama spoke with NASA Astronaut Scott Kelly over the phone to welcome him back to Earth after his record-breaking year-long mission on the International Space Station. The President expressed gratitude for Kelly's service, his use of social media to share his journey with people worldwide, and his participation in important research on long space journeys. Obama also commended Kelly for inspiring young people to pursue careers in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics. The President emphasized the importance of Kelly's mission in providing valuable data for researchers aiming to understand how to keep astronauts healthy during long space voyages. Furthermore, Obama stated that this mission aligns with his vision of sending American astronauts to Mars in the 2030s. The President believes that, thanks to Kelly's work and the efforts of NASA and the U.S. space industry, the United States will successfully reach Mars and continue to lead and inspire the world in space exploration.